meaning: n.马克思主义adj.马克思的；马克思主义的马克思主义            Marxism and capitalism are very different economic ideas.马克思主义和资本主义是两个非常不同的经济理论。      来自德国 19 世纪政治理论家 Karl Marx, -ism, 主义, 思想.      noun [ U ]uk/ˈmɑːk.sɪ.zəm/ us/ˈmɑːrk.sɪ.zəm/   a social, political, and economic theory that is based on the writings of Karl Marx马克思主义       Use the noun Marxism to describe a particular theory of economics and politics that endorses communism and objects to capitalism.A person who believes in the political philosophy of Marxism is called a Marxist. Both words come from the name of the man who first developed the ideas behind Marxism, Karl Marx. A Hindu is a person who believes in the religion called Hinduism. Many Hindus live in India.Use the term Hindu to talk about someone who follows the teachings and practices of Hinduism, or who has a cultural connection to Hinduism. If you're a Hindu, you belong to the third largest religion in the world, and one with many different gods and goddesses. full_meaning: n.克里奥尔人；克里奥耳语adj.克里奥尔人的；克里奥耳式法语的；克里奥尔语的克利奥尔人的 ，克利奥尔语的 ，克利奥尔式法语的                  词源同 create, 创造. 原指欧洲殖民者, 特别是西班牙人在南美, 加勒比海区域与当地人生育的后代, 后来也指这些后代所使用的语言, 比较 pidgin, Tok Pisin.      noun [ C or U ]uk/kriˈəʊl/ us/kriˈoʊl/   a language that has developed from a mixture of languages（多种语言混合形成的）混合语 creole-speaking tribes讲混合语的部落  nounuk/kriˈəʊl/ us/kriˈoʊl/  Creole noun LANGUAGE  [ C or U ] an American or Caribbean language that is a combination of a European language and another language and is a main language in parts of the southern US and the Caribbean克里奥耳语（一种美洲或加勒比语言，由欧洲语言和其他语言混合而成，是美国南部和加勒比海地区的主要语言）  Creole noun PERSON  [ C ] someone who is related to the first Europeans who came to the Caribbean or the southern US克里奥耳人（第一批前往加勒比地区或美国南部的欧洲人的后裔） [ C ] a person of mixed African and European origin who speaks Creole克里奥耳人（非洲和欧洲的混血儿，说克里奥尔语）       A creole is a language that comes from a simplified version of another language, or the mix of two or more languages. In Haiti, people speak a creole that's mostly based on French.When a new language is a variation on one or more older languages, you can call it a creole. Many creoles arise from the contact between both languages and cultures — Haitian creole sounds similar to French, but it's also influenced by Portuguese, Spanish, and some West African languages, since it emerged from the connection between French colonists and African slaves. Creole comes from the Portuguese crioulo, ""servant raised in one's house.""creole: creoles   Creole
